You are absolutely correct! `std::array` of non-copyable types (like `KBucket` with its `std::mutex`) cannot be assigned. This is a classic C++ thread-safety issue.

### The Cleanest Solution: Remove Assignment Operator

We don't actually need to copy `DHTRoutingTable` objects in our design. The `DHT` class owns one routing table and never needs to copy it. Let's simplify:

---

### 1. Update `include/network/DHT.hpp`

Remove the assignment operator and add `Initialize()` method:

```cpp
class DHTRoutingTable {
public:
    // Default constructor
    DHTRoutingTable();

    // Constructor with node ID
    DHTRoutingTable(const uint8_t* local_node_id);

    // NEW: Initialize with node ID (instead of assignment)
    void Initialize(const uint8_t* local_node_id);

    // ... rest of existing methods ...

    // DELETED: operator= (not needed, mutex makes copying unsafe anyway)

private:
    uint8_t m_local_node_id[DHT_NODE_ID_SIZE];
    std::array<KBucket, 160> m_buckets;
    mutable std::mutex m_mutex;
    bool m_initialized;

    int GetBucketIndex(const uint8_t* node_id) const;
};
```

---

### 2. Update `src/network/DHT.cpp`

Remove the assignment operator and fix `DHT::Initialize()`:

```cpp
// DHTRoutingTable Implementation
DHTRoutingTable::DHTRoutingTable() : m_initialized(false) {
    memset(m_local_node_id, 0, DHT_NODE_ID_SIZE);
}

DHTRoutingTable::DHTRoutingTable(const uint8_t* local_node_id) : m_initialized(true) {
    memcpy(m_local_node_id, local_node_id, DHT_NODE_ID_SIZE);
}

// NEW: Initialize method (instead of assignment)
void DHTRoutingTable::Initialize(const uint8_t* local_node_id) {
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(m_mutex);
    memcpy(m_local_node_id, local_node_id, DHT_NODE_ID_SIZE);
    m_initialized = true;
    // Note: We don't clear buckets - they can be reused
}

// ... rest of existing methods (AddNode, UpdateNode, GetClosestNodes, etc.) ...

// DHT Implementation
DHT::DHT() : m_identity(nullptr), m_socket(nullptr), m_running(false) {
    memset(m_local_node_id, 0, DHT_NODE_ID_SIZE);
    // m_routingTable uses default constructor - no assignment needed!
}

bool DHT::Initialize(const Crypto::Identity* identity) {
    if (!identity || !identity->IsValid()) {
        return false;
    }

    m_identity = identity;

    // Generate Node ID = SHA1 hash of public key
    std::string pubkey_pem = identity->GetPublicKeyPEM();
    mbedtls_sha1_context ctx;
    mbedtls_sha1_init(&ctx);
    mbedtls_sha1_starts(&ctx);
    mbedtls_sha1_update(&ctx, 
        reinterpret_cast<const unsigned char*>(pubkey_pem.c_str()),
        pubkey_pem.size());
    mbedtls_sha1_finish(&ctx, m_local_node_id);
    mbedtls_sha1_free(&ctx);

    // FIXED: Use Initialize() instead of assignment
    m_routingTable.Initialize(m_local_node_id);

    std::cout << "[DHT] Initialized with Node ID: ";
    for (int i = 0; i < 8; ++i) {
        printf("%02x", m_local_node_id[i]);
    }
    std::cout << std::endl;

    return true;
}
```

---

### 3. Also Fix: `KBucket` Copy Constructor (For Array Initialization)

If `std::array` still complains, add an explicit copy constructor to `KBucket`:

```cpp
class KBucket {
public:
    KBucket() = default;

    // Explicit copy constructor (for std::array)
    KBucket(const KBucket& other) {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(other.m_mutex);
        m_entries = other.m_entries;
    }

    // Copy assignment (if needed)
    KBucket& operator=(const KBucket& other) {
        if (this != &other) {
            std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(m_mutex);
            std::lock_guard<std::mutex> otherLock(other.m_mutex);
            m_entries = other.m_entries;
        }
        return *this;
    }

    // ... rest of existing methods ...

private:
    std::vector<KBucketEntry> m_entries;
    mutable std::mutex m_mutex;
};
```

---

### Summary of Fixes

| Issue | Problem | Solution |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `std::array` assignment | `KBucket` has `std::mutex` (non-copyable) | Remove `operator=` from `DHTRoutingTable` |
| `DHT::Initialize()` | Tried to assign routing table | Use `Initialize()` method instead |
| `KBucket` copy | May be needed for array operations | Add explicit copy constructor |

---

### Why This Is Better

1. ✅ **No unsafe copying** - Mutexes shouldn't be copied anyway
2. ✅ **Clearer lifecycle** - `Initialize()` makes intent explicit
3. ✅ **Thread-safe** - No race conditions during copy
4. ✅ **Simpler code** - Less boilerplate

Apply these changes and the compilation should succeed! 🚀

